nd":{"line":54,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We have to ask in all sincerity whether the study of the history of the church ought not to be completely redesigned. (David Bosch)","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"key":"fcUxZPkic7"}],"key":"lPg5vnpCE9"}],"key":"g7Fk9qBQ2L"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":56,"column":1},"end":{"line":56,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"These quotes highlight the importance of approaching church history with a missional and contextual perspective. We should not just focus on doctrinal disputes but also on how the gospel has been communicated and lived out in different cultural settings.","position":{"start":{"line":56,"column":1},"end":{"line":56,"column":1}},"key":"NLd06ENpl6"}],"key":"Gv7162R6uW"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"To provide a tool for studying church history, Prof. Rylaarsdam introduced us the two principles for missional encounters with culture:","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"key":"HlFktEK0Y3"}],"key":"D9STMwhUk7"},{"type":"list","ordered":true,"start":1,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":1},"end":{"line":63,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":1},"end":{"line":61,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":1},"end":{"line":61,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The indigenizing principle:","position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":1},"end":{"line":61,"column":1}},"key":"D2gv1TJuZp"}],"key":"vsW8SmgU0F"},{"type":"text","value":" Christianity enters a culture and finds customs that embody the way of Christ. Christians celebrate the culture. They are residents in it.","position":{"start":{"line":61,"column":1},"end":{"line":61,"colu